    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.25.17-20_0001"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">17</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>9 - 21</dateline>
                
                    <salute>Dear Dr. Neihardt,</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I surely miss you and your little flock of "Critical Essayists." I won't be in school until February, since I'm tied up here with some business affairs of my mother's.</p>
                
                <p>Link has my <hi rend="underline">Cycle of the West</hi>, I'm perfectly content to pick it up in Feb. However, if he's leaving school or won't be there for some reason, will you tell him he can leave it with you or Mrs. Motman (?). She wanted to read it, too.</p>
                
                <p>And please tell the brethren and cistern (!) of our old class
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.25.17-20_0002"/>
                
                    <fw type="authorial">2</fw>
                    <fw type="curatorial">18</fw>
                
                    hello; I think of all of you often. That course was nerve-wracking but quite helpful.</p>
                
                <p>I've just read Nevil Shute's <hi rend="underline">On the Beach</hi>, and it reminds me of <hi rend="underline">Red Snow</hi> (remember my essay, that I didn't write?). This is a real shocker; he paints such a plausible picture, you can just see the whole world dying slowly of radiation poisoning. He has tailored his work so well, the story doesn't seem to have been <del/> pored over at all. You know, "hard writing, easy reading."</p>
                
                <p>I had to buy it to compare
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.25.17-20_0003"/>
                    
                    <fw type="authorial">2</fw>
                    <fw type="curatorial">19</fw>
                
                    his technique and thinking with that of the unknown who wrote <hi rend="underline">Red Snow</hi>. <hi rend="underline">On the Beach</hi> reads easier and is more realistic; the characters have more substance.</p>
                
                <p>Would you like to read it? I'll send it to you, or I may be up there in a few weeks (to see Miss Stout, of course.), and I'll bring it along.</p>
                
                <p>Oh yes, Judy Crow of Cape Girardeau<del>,</del> says she remembers you (favorably) from a Writers Guild meeting. She works on the <hi rend="caps">C. G.</hi> <hi rend="underline">Missourian</hi> and is afflicted with cerebral palsy.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>With kind thoughts,</salute>
                    <signed>Odell Williams</signed>
                </closer>
                
                <postscript>
                    <p><hi rend="underline">Sold my 2nd Article!</hi></p>
                </postscript>
                
            </div1>
            
            
